Date: Sat 25 Nov 2017
Source: Bournemouth Echo [edited]
http://www.bournemouthecho.co.uk/news/15683701.Rabbits_in_Dorset_at_risk_from_fatal_disease__pet_owners_warned/


Rabbits are at risk from a fatal 'new to Dorset' disease, according to vets. Dave Cumber Vets in Weymouth have recently treated 4 fatal cases of the rabbit disease. The 1st confirmed case was in Blandford in August this year [2017].

The surgery is now advising rabbit owners in Dorset to have their pets vaccinated against a newer strain of viral haemorrhagic diarrhoea - VHD2. Dave Cumber said: "Most of our rabbit-owning clients have their pets vaccinated annually with a combined vaccine against myxomatosis and VHD1. This November [2017] we have had 4 very sick rabbits brought into our Weymouth surgery and sadly all have died. The cause of death has been established at post mortem to be the VHD2 disease. The standard combined vaccine will not protect your pet against VHD2, and we strongly recommend that all rabbit owners in the area consider having their pets further vaccinated with a specific vaccine against VHD2. The 1st confirmed case of VHD2 in Dorset was in Blandford in August this year [2017] and these 4 cases are the 1st we know of in Weymouth to be confirmed as VHD2."

If your pet rabbit starts to display any of the following signs then contact the vet immediately as the disease is highly contagious and can be fatal: generally off colour, not eating and listlessness.

[byline: Jade Grassby]

