[Rabbit haemorrhagic disease (RHD) is a highly contagious and acute fatal hepatitis of the European rabbit (_Oryctolagus cuniculus_) caused by a calicivirus (genus _Lagovirus_). It is one of the 2 notifiable infectious diseases of Leporidae included in OIE's list (the other one is myxomatosis).

Up to 2010, all RHD viruses (RHDV) isolated belonged to one of the 6 identified genotypes (GI-GVI), among which the GVI is an antigenic subtype (RHDVa). In 2010, an additional RHDV was identified, phylogenetically and antigenically distinct from RHDV and provisionally called RHDV2 or RHDVb. A similar disease, termed European brown hare syndrome (EBHS), has been described in the hare (_Lepus europaeus_).

RHD is characterised by high morbidity and a mortality of 70-90 per cent for RHDV/RHDVa and 5-70 per cent for RHDV2. Infection mainly occurs by the oral route. In wild rabbits in particular, insects are considered an important route of infection or transmission, and are often the source of long-distance spread. The incubation period of RHD varies from one to 3 days, and death usually occurs 12-36 hours after the onset of fever. The main clinical manifestations of the acute infection are nervous and respiratory signs, apathy and anorexia. In rabbits younger than 4-6 weeks, the RHDV/RHDVa infection course is subclinical, but when the causative agent is RHDV2, clinical signs and mortality are observed even in young animals from 15 to 20 days of age onwards.

Requirements for vaccines: indirect control of the disease is easily achieved by vaccination. Although the capsid RHDVs has been expressed as recombinant VPLs, as of 2015 the vaccines used are inactivated vaccine prepared from livers of experimentally infected rabbits, and thus inactivated and adjuvanated. Vaccinated animals quickly produce solid protective immunity against RHDV infection (within 7-10 days), and experimental data indicate that protection lasts for a long period (over one year). As RHDV2 is a distant antigenic subtype or even a 2nd RHDV serotype, combined vaccination with both antigenic types, or the use of a vaccine homologous to the RHDV strain identified during the epidemics or the outbreak, is highly advisable.

The above and additional information on RHD is available in OIE's terrestrial Manual chapter 2.6.2, "Rabbit Haemorrhagic Disease," at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.06.02_RHD.pdf. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5465175,279.]
